				 Teacher faces jail in Sudan
																								Khartoum, Nov. 28 (Reuters): A British teacher detained in Sudan after her class called a teddy bear Mohammad was charged today with insulting Islam in a move that sparked a diplomatic row between London and Khartoum.																								Gillian Gibbons, 54, was also charged with inciting hatred and showing contempt for religious beliefs, Sudanese official media said. If convicted, she could face 40 lashes, a fine, or one year in jail.																								Khartoum North prosecution unit has completed its investigation and has charged the Briton Gillian (Gibbons) under Article 125 of the criminal code, the Sudanese news agency SUNA said. 
